Great—let’s design a Pantheon Idea Passport so ideas can move cleanly through the ecosystem. Think of it as a compact record that travels from Signal Tower → Observatory, capturing what matters at each stage.

⸻

Pantheon Idea Passport (Field Format)

Header

Title:
Originator:
Date:
Domain(s):
Stage: [Signal Tower / Bazaar / Campfires / Thunderdome / Cathedral / Garden / Observatory]
Evidence Level: 0–4

Evidence Ladder

0 — speculation
1 — analogy / pattern hint
2 — model / structured argument
3 — experiment or prototype
4 — validated principle


⸻

Core Insight Section

Observation (Signal Tower)

What anomaly or weak signal triggered this idea?

Pattern (Bazaar)

What repeating structure or invariant appears?
Which domains show it?

Narrative (Campfires)

Explain the idea in one short story or metaphor.

Challenge (Thunderdome)

Evidence supporting it:
Failure scenario:
Simpler competing explanation:

Verification Plan (Cathedral)

Prediction:
Experiment or prototype path:
Measurement criteria:

Evolution Path (Garden)

Possible mutations or extensions:
Related ideas for recombination:

Strategic Value (Observatory)

Why does this matter?
What frontier might it open?


⸻

Compression Section

One Sentence Version

[idea in one sentence]

Symbolic Form (optional)

pattern → test → result

Tags

invariants
cross-domain
high curiosity gradient
needs prototype


⸻

Passport Lifecycle

Signal Tower → idea detected
Bazaar → idea explored
Campfires → idea communicated
Thunderdome → idea challenged
Cathedral → idea tested
Garden → idea evolves
Observatory → idea mapped strategically

Ideas can loop back if they fail or mutate.

⸻

Example (short)

Title: Curiosity Gradient
Stage: Bazaar
Evidence: 1

Observation:

Some questions generate many more questions.

Pattern:

Discovery tends to follow expanding question networks.

Narrative:

Curiosity behaves like a hill-climbing algorithm.

Challenge:

Could this simply be novelty bias?

Verification:

Track research progress vs question branching rate.


⸻

Why This Helps

The passport prevents two common problems:
	•	idea loss (good insights vanish in conversation)
	•	idea inflation (untested ideas appear stronger than they are)

It also creates a traceable path of reasoning.

